====== WikiLAN ======

LAN-party manager as a DokuWiki plugin. Install by placing this directory at
lib/plugins/wikilan/ and running the install CLI command below.

===== Syntax modules =====

  ~~LAN:attendance~~            attend-toggle + roster (arrived auto-detected)
  ~~LAN:seating~~               inline SVG plan + hotspots + table fallback
                                (show=both|plan|table for split layouts)
  ~~LAN:calendar~~              fahrplan-style event calendar (struct-backed)
  ~~LAN:eventsignup~~           interested/signed-up buttons on event pages
  ~~LAN:notify~~                embedded notice feed (room display)
  ~~LAN:when~~                  inline schedule date, localized to the page
                                language (buildup|start|end, date|time|datetime)
  ~~LAN:profile~~               steam-style card: avatar, persona, presence,
                                friend/profile deeplinks, stat tiles, played
                                games split current-LAN vs lifetime, LANs
                                attended, strichliste buy stats
  ~~LAN:sharedgames~~           owned-library intersection picker
                                (multiplayer-only + min-players filters;
                                player counts from PCGamingWiki, resolved
                                lazily by cron — unknown counts pass filters)
  ~~LAN:strichliste~~           buy statistics from the read-only strichliste
                                MySQL: top articles + top buyers for the
                                context LAN's window (buildup→end) and
                                all-time (limit=, alltime=0, user= for a
                                one-line personal summary)

All modules take lan=<neutral ns> (default: edition derived from the page id,
else the active LAN). Seating takes plan=<media id> to override the LAN's SVG.

===== Data flow =====

  * Edition state machine: planned → active → archived (admin/CLI flip;
    only one active). Live modules render fresh state; archived render frozen rows.
  * Event pages live under <lang>:msl:<year>_<n>:events:* with the struct
    'event' schema (day, starttime, duration [min], host, category, price [€],
    cutoffday, cutofftime). Signups/attendance/seats are keyed by
    language-neutral ids.
  * Food/paid events: set price + signup cutoff (fahrplan-relative day, time
    defaults to 23:59). Signups carry an optional comment; state changes are
    blocked after the cutoff (mods excepted). Payment: users book a
    strichliste transaction of the exact price with the event's payment code
    (the page name) as comment, OR — preferred, kiosk-compatible — buy the
    strichliste product whose id is set on the event (productid field; the
    matcher follows the article precursor_id version chain, since editing a
    strichliste product creates a new id). Cron reconciles via read-only
    access to the strichliste MySQL (sqlquery plugin credentials, strichliste
    usernames == wiki logins by site convention — per-user overrides in the
    admin page's name-mapping table) and flags signups paid.
    Mods can toggle paid manually (cash) on the signup list.
  * Event scheduling is fahrplan-relative: day 1 = the edition's start day,
    0/-1/… are buildup days (day N → start + N-1 days). Rescheduling the
    edition (lan-dates) moves all events automatically.
  * Users create events via the bureaucracy form <edition>:events:new
    (linked under ~~LAN:calendar~~; struct data saved by struct's
    bureaucracy integration, page from msl:event_template). install /
    lan-create seed those pages plus namespace _template.txt skeletons for
    manually created event and msl:users:* pages. events:start and
    events:new are reserved (never listed as events).
  * Edition schedule: buildup / start / end-aka-teardown-start datetimes on
    the lans row (admin page or `lan-dates`). ~~LAN:when~~ embeds them in
    pages so content follows schedule changes; missing dates render a
    localized "date TBA".
  * Seat map: one seat per user. Clicking a free seat while already holding
    one (reserved OR arrived) never moves silently — the server replies with
    a confirm prompt; only the re-request with move=1 releases the old seat.
  * Buddy seats: label a second spot 'A1b' in the plan SVG (position marker,
    hidden in the rendered plan) and re-import — seats-import creates the
    A1b row with buddy_of=A1. Solo, one circle sits at the midpoint of the
    two labels; once a buddy is seated, two full-size circles sit at their
    own labeled spots. Buddy spots can't be reserved directly: the seat
    holder shares their table (click own seat → share dropdown of seatless
    attendees; the buddy gets a notice + push) or a mod assigns via the
    admin page. Port-map the buddy spot like any seat ('port-set <ns>
    <port> A1b <ip>') and arrival detection works as usual.
  * Arrival: port↔seat↔IP map (admin page or `port-set`); a logged-in request
    from a mapped IP marks the user arrived — but only onto their first/own
    seat. If they already hold a different seat, nothing moves automatically:
    a banner offers a one-click confirmed move (target re-resolved from the
    client IP server-side). Organizer overrides via the admin page.
  * Notifications: notices table → site-wide widget (30s poll) + Web Push
    (VAPID keys auto-generated, stored in sqlite opts). Cron flushes outbox.
  * User chips (rosters, signup lists) and occupied seats link to the user's
    profile page …:msl:users:<login>; occupied plan hotspots show the Steam
    avatar. A logged-in user visiting their own missing profile page gets a
    plain HTML creation form (about/clan/games/hardware — no markup needed);
    the page is generated from those fields and stays normally editable.
  * Steam linking: User Tools → Steam (?do=wikilan_steam) works with every
    auth backend (LDAP included). The ?do=profile fieldset only appears for
    backends that allow profile editing. Persona name + avatar are cached at
    link time and refreshed by the now-playing sync; rosters fall back to the
    wiki name + a lettered placeholder avatar for unlinked users.

===== CLI =====

  php bin/plugin.php wikilan install            # db, struct schemas, vapid
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan cron               # every minute (cron.d/wikilan)
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan lan-create [--start=… --end=… --plan=…] <ns> <title>
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan lan-state <ns> <planned|active|archived>
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan lan-dates [--buildup=… --start=… --end=…] <ns>
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan seats-import <ns>  # seed seats from plan SVG labels
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan port-set <ns> <port> <seat> <ip>
  php bin/plugin.php wikilan push-test <user>
  (options must come BEFORE positional arguments)

===== Seating plan SVG =====

Draw the plan in Inkscape; label each seat with a text code matching
^[A-Z]{1,2}[0-9]+$ (e.g. A1, C12). The renderer injects a hotspot circle over
each label. Alternative: name any shape with the seat code in the Objects
panel (inkscape:label) and that shape becomes the hit area. Re-import after
changing the SVG (admin page button or seats-import).

===== Admin =====

Admin → WikiLAN: editions & state, plan media, seat flags/assignments,
port map, wrong-seat mismatches, strichliste name mapping, broadcasts.
Occupied seat rows carry
one-click actions on the current holder (set arrived / unarrive / clear);
the assign form is an attendee dropdown for seating someone else. Mods (group 'lanmod',
configurable) get seat overrides + broadcasts; edition management is
admin-only. NOTE: DokuWiki only offers admin pages to managers — mods
additionally need $conf['manager'] = '@lanmod' (set in local.php) or
they never see the WikiLAN admin entry.
